not really welcome in my house.


92
0:3:49,52 --> 0:3:51,69
And books were considered
a waste of time.


93
0:3:51,69 --> 0:3:55,19
And my father was
a violent alcoholic


94
0:3:55,19 --> 0:3:58,71
who made my childhood
a kind of-- I


95
0:3:58,71 --> 0:4:0,21
had to escape into books.


96
0:4:0,21 --> 0:4:2,58
But I had to hide the
fact that I had books,


97
0:4:2,58 --> 0:4:5,39
or that I was getting
them out of the library.


98
0:4:5,39 --> 0:4:8,4
And that audience, suddenly,
I lost them entirely.


99
0:4:8,4 --> 0:4:9,234
They just went dead.


100
0:4:9,234 --> 0:4:10,941
And they were all
looking at me, like-- I


101
0:4:10,941 --> 0:4:12,33
realized, oh, I blew it.


102
0:4:12,33 --> 0:4:15,94
Now they think I've had
a terrible childhood.


103
0:4:15,94 --> 0:4:18,19
And it wasn't a
terrible childhood.


104
0:4:18,19 --> 0:4:21,795
I always felt happiness is
a choice, no matter what


105
0:4:21,795 --> 0:4:22,67
you're going through.


106
0:4:22,67 --> 0:4:24,65
And as a kid, there
were things I liked.


107
0:4:24,65 --> 0:4:25,91
One of them was books.


108
0:4:25,91 --> 0:4:29,3
And another was I got a
bike that an uncle gave me.


109
0:4:29,3 --> 0:4:33,2
And I could travel 30 miles,
40 miles a day on that bike,


110
0:4:33,2 --> 0:4:36,41
and go all over this little
farm town where I was raised.


111
0:4:36,41 --> 0:4:38,21
And I could be away
from that house.


112
0:4:38,21 --> 0:4:39,95
My mother was a great person.


113
0:4:39,95 --> 0:4:42,4
But if my father
was there, the house


114
0:4:42,4 --> 0:4:45,93
was not place anybody
would want to be.


115
0:4:45,93 --> 0:4:47,71
Then I said to
them, but you know,


116
0:4:47,71 --> 0:4:49,55
I don't mean to say
my childhood was bad.


117
0:4:49,55 --> 0:4:51,43
I told them happiness
is a choice.


118
0:4:51,43 --> 0:4:54,84
And I said also my father
had a funny side to him.


119
0:4:54,84 --> 0:4:56,62
He was a very good salesman.


120
0:4:56,62 --> 0:5:1,9
He could get people to invest
in inventions that he created.


121
0:5:1,9 --> 0:5:3,78
And he could actually
raise significant money


122
0:5:3,78 --> 0:5:7,34
for those days to
produce the invention


123
0:5:7,34 --> 0:5:10,84
in a number of copies, hundreds
of them, thousands of them,


124
0:5:10,84 --> 0:5:11,66
warehouse them.


125
0:5:11,66 --> 0:5:14,48
But they were never
anything that he could sell.


126
0:5:14,48 --> 0:5:16,15
You'll see why in just a minute.


127
0:5:16,15 --> 0:5:18,47
But he could get people
to raise the money.


128
0:5:18,47 --> 0:5:21,33
And it always amazed me,
because we never saw the money.


129
0:5:21,33 --> 0:5:23,0
He gambled it away or spent it.


130
0:5:23,0 --> 0:5:26,14
And he often had investors
trying to put him in jail.


131
0:5:26,14 --> 0:5:28,4
And he couldn't
hold onto his money.


132
0:5:28,4 --> 0:5:31,86
But he could invent things
that I thought were absurd,


133
0:5:31,86 --> 0:5:34,81
but some people thought
were good investments.


134
0:5:34,81 --> 0:5:41,53
One of the ones I remember
was he had this big exercise


135
0:5:41,53 --> 0:5:42,5
machine.


136
0:5:42,5 --> 0:5:44,54
And this was in
the days-- he may


137
0:5:44,54 --> 0:5:45,72
have been correct
about this-- he called


138
0:5:45,72 --> 0:5:48,51
it the first electric
exercise machine.


139
0:5:48,51 --> 0:5:52,71
And it may have been
true, that in those days,


140
0:5:52,71 --> 0:5:55,43
treadmills were actually
run by your own power,


141
0:5:55,43 --> 0:5:57,35
and they weren't electric.


142
0:5:57,35 --> 0:6:1,89
But it was about the size of an
old console model television.


143
0:6:1,89 --> 0:6:4,6
I'm the only one here old
enough to remember those.


144
0:6:4,6 --> 0:6:8,26
They were about this high,
and this wide, and that deep--


145
0:6:8,26 --> 0:6:9,8
a huge box.


146
0:6:9,8 --> 0:6:12,66
And this was all it
was, was this huge box.


147
0:6:12,66 --> 0:6:15,28
It had a little hole on
one side, and a hook.


148
0:6:15,28 --> 0:6:16,62
And you pulled the hook out.


149
0:6:16,62 --> 0:6:19,7
And this rope came on the hook.


150
0:6:19,7 --> 0:6:21,61
And then you were supposed
to, into a door frame,


151
0:6:21,61 --> 0:6:25,9
screw a little eye hook, so
that the hook could go into it.


152
0:6:25,9 --> 0:6:28,1
Then you turned on the
electric jump rope.


153
0:6:28,1 --> 0:6:30,74
And an engine or
motor turned it.


154
0:6:30,74 --> 0:6:32,1
And it sounded like this.


155
0:6:32,1 --> 0:6:34,28
[MOTOR NOISES]


156
0:6:34,28 --> 0:6:36,21
And it turned this jump rope.


157
0:6:36,21 --> 0:6:39,307
And I stood there
looking at this machine.


158
0:6:39,307 --> 0:6:41,39
He actually got investors
to produce 200 of these.


159
0:6:41,39 --> 0:6:43,71
He never sold any.


160
0:6:43,71 --> 0:6:48,6
And I said, but Dad, who wants
to buy an electric jump rope?


161
0:6:48,6 --> 0:6:50,57
And he got angry very quickly.


162
0:6:50,57 --> 0:6:53,51
And he said, everybody
will want to buy one.


163
0:6:53,51 --> 0:6:57,5
And I said, but when you're
exercising with the jump rope,


164
0:6:57,5 --> 0:7:1,6
part of the exercise is
the arms, the upper body.


165
0:7:1,6 --> 0:7:2,77
It's not all about the jumping.


166
0:7:2,77 --> 0:7:5,35
And he said, this is for
people who want to exercise,


167
0:7:5,35 --> 0:7:6,575
but not too damn much.


168
0:7:6,575 --> 0:7:9,14
[LAUGHTER]


169
0:7:9,14 --> 0:7:11,31
And I had no answer to that.


170
0:7:11,31 --> 0:7:14,76
And then, because he knew
that I wasn't really approving


171
0:7:14,76 --> 0:7:19,1
of this, he said, this is
also the only exercise machine


172
0:7:19,1 --> 0:7:21,19
that a blind man can use.


173
0:7:21,19 --> 0:7:24,34
And I was really
baffled at that.


174
0:7:24,34 --> 0:7:26,81
And then he pointed out to
me that every time the rope


175
0:7:26,81 --> 0:7:29,68
hit the apex if its
arc, a bell rang.


176
0:7:29,68 --> 0:7:33,12
So a blind man would know when
it was starting to come down.


177
0:7:33,12 --> 0:7:34,674
And a friend of
mine, years later


178
0:7:34,674 --> 0:7:36,9
when I was telling
him this, said,


179
0:7:36,9 --> 0:7:38,64
boy, I could see Ray
Charles in the TV commercial


180
0:7:38,64 --> 0:7:40,93
already, singing
"Ol' Man River,"


181
0:7:40,93 --> 0:7:43,48
and the jump rope coming around.


182
0:7:43,48 --> 0:7:46,11
These were always a great
horrible thing for my mother.


183
0:7:46,11 --> 0:7:50,85
Because my mother knew that when
he got people to invent things,


184
0:7:50,85 --> 0:7:55,16
